      <hedline>
        <hl1>Cell Phone Rage: Helpful Hints</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Joel Conarroe letter endorses Sharon White Taylor's July 5 article deploring discourteous use of cell phones in public; drawing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Sharon White Taylor's description of ''cell phone rage'' (''Wireless and Witless,'' Op-Ed, July 5) rings a bell. An increasing number of restaurants and stores are banning the disruptive little machines. Yet when I've ridden the Long Island Rail Road or Amtrak I've never seen cell-free zones. Just think of the no-smoking cars back when trains were rolling ashtrays.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Sharon White Taylor's description of ''cell phone rage'' (''Wireless and Witless,'' Op-Ed, July 5) rings a bell. An increasing number of restaurants and stores are banning the disruptive little machines. Yet when I've ridden the Long Island Rail Road or Amtrak I've never seen cell-free zones. Just think of the no-smoking cars back when trains were rolling ashtrays.</p>
        <p>This means that those of us who would rather read, sleep or daydream than listen to the braying of our fellow travelers regularly experience what can only be described as ''railroad rage.''</p>
        <p>JOEL CONARROE  Amagansett, N.Y., July 5, 2000</p>
      </block>
